{"add":{"doc":{"id":"6efa211d2ef018fb05e3dd3344ca37139cfac856de18534c338e2893594052ac","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Rothermere_-_Hurrah_for_the_Blackshirts.jpg/220px-Rothermere_-_Hurrah_for_the_Blackshirts.jpg","previous":[],"after":["Lord Rothermere was a friend of Benito Mussolini and Adolf Hitler, and directed the Mail's editorial stance towards them in the early 1930s.[32][33] Rothermere's 1933 leader \"Youth Triumphant\" praised the new Nazi regime's accomplishments, and was subsequently used as propaganda by them.[34] In it, Rothermere predicted that \"The minor misdeeds of individual Nazis would be submerged by the immense benefits the new regime is already bestowing upon Germany\". Journalist John Simpson, in a book on journalism, suggested that Rothermere was referring to the violence against Jews and Communists rather than the detention of political prisoners.[35]"]}}}